    Astro allows you to configure a type-safe schema for your environment variables, and converts variables imported via astro:env into the expected type. This is the recommended way to use environment variables in Astro, as it allows you to easily see and manage whether your variables are public or secret, available on the client or only on the server at build time, and the data type of your values.

    However, you can still access environment variables through process.env and import.meta.env directly when needed. This was the only way to use environment variables in Astro before astro:env was added in Astro 5.0, and Astro's default handling of import.meta.env includes some logic that was only needed for earlier versions of Astro.

    The experimental.staticImportMetaEnv flag updates the behavior of import.meta.env to align with Vite's handling of environment variables and for better ease of use with Astro's current implementations and features. This will become the default behavior in Astro 6.0, and this early preview is introduced as an experimental feature.

    Currently, non-public import.meta.env environment variables are replaced by a reference to process.env. Additionally, Astro may also convert the value type of your environment variables used through import.meta.env, which can prevent access to some values such as the strings "true" (which is converted to a boolean value), and "1" (which is converted to a number).

feat: Implement dynamic NVDEC decoder reconfiguration

This commit implements dynamic reconfiguration for the client-side NVDEC decoder to handle changes in video stream resolution.

The key changes are:
- Added `FrameDecoder::RecreateDecoder` to orchestrate the destruction and recreation of the decoder and its associated D3D12/CUDA resources.
- Implemented `FrameDecoder::DestroyDecoderResources` for safe and complete cleanup of all decoder-related resources.
- The `HandleVideoSequence` callback now detects format changes (resolution, chroma format, etc.) and triggers the reconfiguration process.
- When the decoder is reconfigured, the rendering and reordering queues are cleared to prevent artifacts from stale frames.
- The current `CUVIDEOFORMAT` is now stored in the `FrameDecoder` class to ensure accurate comparisons for detecting format changes.

This allows the client to seamlessly adapt when the server changes the streaming resolution, for example, after the client window is resized.

issue.title: VIm with `vim-lsp` won't load local config files
issue.body:
### The context:

VIm (as in vim.org, not neovim) users often use [`prabirshrestha/vim-lsp`](https://github.com/prabirshrestha/vim-lsp/) to provide LSP support.

### The issue:

By default, the current version of `vim-lsp` (`master`=[`04428c9`](https://github.com/prabirshrestha/vim-lsp/tree/04428c920002ac7cfacbecacb070a8af57b455d0) as of 2025-08-17) doesn't send workspace folder info to LSP servers (including `typos-lsp`). Consequently, `typos-lsp` never loads config files from the current project. No relevant diagnostic messages are emitted, even with `RUST_LOG=trace`.

A fix is described below.

Suggested steps to resolve:

- add this info to `typos-lsp`'s documentation
  - since `vim-lsp` says the "experimental" feature in question will be enabled by default in a future release:
    - document this, and
    - advise users to check [`vim-lsp.txt`](https://github.com/mattn/vim-lsp-settings/blob/master/doc/vim-lsp-settings.txt) heading `vim-lsp-workspace-folders` for the current status
      - users may prefer to use this VIm command: `:help vim-lsp-workspace-folders`
    - you might ask users to file a bug if the situation changes, so any outdated documentation can be removed
- it might also be worth issuing a diagnostic message when no workspace folder info is available

### The fix:

Quoting from the current [`vim-lsp.txt`](https://github.com/prabirshrestha/vim-lsp/blob/0094b5e0fc7db02e0a35d942e5e7f2069ccdbbfc/doc/vim-lsp.txt#L2259):
```vimhelp
==============================================================================
Workspace Folders                                  *vim-lsp-workspace-folders*

Workspace folders is an experimental feature of vim-lsp. To enable workspace
folders set `let g:lsp_experimental_workspace_folders = 1`. In the future this
flag will be removed and workspace folders will be enabled by default.

When a new buffer is opened, if the server supports workspace folder, it will
call `root_uri` function to detect the workspace folder. If the folder is not
part of workspace folder, it will automatically notify the server to add the
workspace folder.

=============================================================================
```

**In other words, add this to your `.vimrc`:**
```vim
let g:lsp_experimental_workspace_folders = 1
```
